AmBev, Cemig, Bancolombia, Gerdau: Latin America Equity Preview

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 
2011-03-17T06:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-17/ambev-cemig-bancolombia-gerdau-latin-america-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  The MSCI Latin America Index fell 1.6 percent to 4,324.87.    Brazil   Steelmakers: Banco do Brasil SA Chief Executive Officer
Aldemir Bendine said the bank is analyzing possible project
finance investments of 85 billion reais ($50.8 billion), mostly
in infrastructure. Bendine spoke yesterday in Brasilia.    Gerdau SA (GGBR4)  (GGBR4 BS), Brazil’s biggest steelmaker, declined
3.2 percent to 21.42 reais.  Cia. Energetica de  Minas Gerais  (CMIG4 BS): Cemig, the
state-controlled electricity utility, and Petroleo Brasileiro SA
(PETR4 BS), Brazil’s state-controlled oil producer, plan to sign
a memorandum of understanding to build a $1.3 billion nitrogen-
based fertilizer plant in Brazil’s Minas Gerais state. The
companies also plan to build a pipeline. Cemig fell 2.7 percent
to 28.56 reais. Petrobras slid 0.9 percent to 27.78 reais.  Cia. de Bebidas das Americas (AMBV4 BS): Anheuser-Busch
InBev NV plans to invest 2.5 billion reais in Brazil this year
to expand capacity, Chief Executive Officer Carlos Brito told
reporters yesterday in Brasilia. InBev will start building a
factory in Pernambuco state and generate 20,000 jobs this year,
he said. AmBev, as Latin America’s largest brewer is known,
declined 2.1 percent to 44 reais.    Colombia   Banks: Colombia’s credit rating was boosted to investment
grade by  Standard & Poor’s , 11 years after it was cut to junk in
the midst of an insurgency, as violence recedes and growth
prospects improve. S&P raised Colombia one step to BBB-, from
BB+. The increase puts Colombia’s rating in line with that of
Brazil and  Peru .    Bancolombia SA (BCOLO)  , the country’s biggest lender,
rose 0.5 percent to 27,600 pesos.    Mexico   Cemex SAB (CEMEXCPO MM): The largest cement maker in the
Americas will pay off its 06-3 bond series, floating-rate
securities due in 2012, on March 24, according to a statement to
the Mexican stock exchange. The company also completed the sale
of $1.67 billion in convertible bonds, including an over-
allotment option granted to managers of the sale. Cemex lost 2.3
percent to 10.32 pesos.  Telefonos de Mexico SAB (TELMEXL MM): Mexico’s largest
fixed-line provider proposed a dividend of 55 centavos a share
and will ask shareholders to vote on its plan to divide into two
companies at an April 4 meeting. The stock rose 0.9 percent to
10.28 pesos.  Peru    Sienna Gold Inc. (SGP)  : The Canadian company plans to
start a gold mine in Peru by 2013, Chief Executive Officer John
Rucci said. Sienna, which began trading its Toronto-listed
shares in  Lima  on March 8, rose 2.9 percent to 0.7 soles.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Leon Lazaroff in New York 
